# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lithium-tantalate-data-page
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/abbe-number] In optics and lens design, the **Abbe number**, also known as the **Vd-number** or **constringence** of a transparent material, is an approximate measure of a material's dispersion (change in refractive index as a function of wavelength), with high Vd values indicating low dispersion.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/abbe-number] It is named after Ernst Abbe (1840–1905), the German physicist who defined it.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/abbe-number] The term Vd-number should not be confused with the normalized frequency in fibers.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/abbe-number] This formulation only applies to human vision; outside this range, alternative spectral lines are required.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/abbe-number] For non-visible spectral lines, the term "V-number" is more commonly used.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/abbe-number] The more general formulation is $V\equiv {\frac {n_{\text{center}}-1}{n_{\text{short}}-n_{\text{long}}}},$ where $n_{\text{short}}$ , $n_{\text{center}}$ , and $n_{\text{long}}$ are the refractive indices of the material at three different wavelengths.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/abbe-number] Abbe numbers are used to classify glass and other optical materials in terms of their chromaticity.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/abbe-number] For example, the higher dispersion flint glasses have relatively small Abbe numbers V less than 55, whereas the lower dispersion crown glasses have larger Abbe numbers.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/abbe-number] Values of $V_{\text{d}}$ range from below 25 for very dense flint glasses, around 34 for polycarbonate plastics, up to 65 for common crown glasses, and 75 to 85 for some fluorite and phosphate crown glasses.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/abbe-number] Abbe numbers are useful in the design of achromatic lenses, as their reciprocal is proportional to dispersion (slope of refractive index versus wavelength) in the domain where the human eye is most sensitive (see above figure).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/abbe-number] For other wavelength regions, or for higher precision in characterizing a system's chromaticity (such as in the design of apochromats), the full dispersion relation is used (i.e., refractive index as a function of wavelength).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/abbe-number] An **Abbe diagram** (sometimes referred to as "the glass veil") is produced by plotting the refractive index of a material $n_{\text{d}}$ as a function of Abbe number V .
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/abbe-number] Glasses can then be categorized and selected according to their positions on the diagram.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/abbe-number] This categorization could be in the form of a letter-number code, as used for example in the Schott Glass catalogue, or a 6-digit glass code.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/abbe-number] Glasses' Abbe numbers, along with their mean refractive indices, are used in the calculation of the required refractive powers of the elements of achromatic lenses in order to cancel chromatic aberration to first order.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/abbe-number] These two parameters, which enter into the equations for the design of achromatic doublets, are exactly what is plotted on an Abbe diagram.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/abbe-number] Due to the difficulty and inconvenience in producing sodium and hydrogen lines, alternate definitions of the Abbe number are often substituted (ISO 7944).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/abbe-number] Other definitions can be similarly employed; the following table lists standard wavelengths at which n is commonly determined, including the standard subscripts used.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/abbe-number] The difference in power can be expressed relative to the power at a center wavelength $\lambda _{\text{c}}$ : $P_{\text{c}}=(n_{\text{c}}-1)\left({\frac {1}{R_{1}}}-{\frac {1}{R_{2}}}\right),$ with $n_{\text{c}}$ having an analogous meaning as above.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] Molecular geometry influences several properties of a substance including its reactivity, polarity, phase of matter, color, magnetism and biological activity.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] The angles between bonds that an atom forms depend only weakly on the rest of a molecule, i.e. they can be understood as approximately local and hence transferable properties.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] The molecular geometry can be determined by various spectroscopic methods and diffraction methods.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] IR, microwave and Raman spectroscopy can give information about the molecule geometry from the details of the vibrational and rotational absorbance detected by these techniques.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] X-ray crystallography, neutron diffraction and electron diffraction can give molecular structure for crystalline solids based on the distance between nuclei and concentration of electron density.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] Gas electron diffraction can be used for small molecules in the gas phase.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] NMR and FRET methods can be used to determine complementary information including relative distances, dihedral angles, angles, and connectivity.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] Molecular geometries are best determined at low temperature because at higher temperatures the molecular structure is averaged over more accessible geometries (see next section).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] Larger molecules often exist in multiple stable geometries (conformational isomerism) that are close in energy on the potential energy surface.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] Geometries can also be computed by ab initio quantum chemistry methods to high accuracy.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] The molecular geometry can be different as a solid, in solution, and as a gas.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] The position of each atom is determined by the nature of the chemical bonds by which it is connected to its neighboring atoms.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] The molecular geometry can be described by the positions of these atoms in space, evoking bond lengths of two joined atoms, bond angles of three connected atoms, and torsion angles (dihedral angles) of three consecutive bonds.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] Since the motions of the atoms in a molecule are determined by quantum mechanics, "motion" must be defined in a quantum mechanical way.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] The overall (external) quantum mechanical motions translation and rotation hardly change the geometry of the molecule.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] The molecular vibrations are harmonic (at least to good approximation), and the atoms oscillate about their equilibrium positions, even at the absolute zero of temperature.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] At higher temperatures the vibrational modes may be thermally excited (in a classical interpretation one expresses this by stating that "the molecules will vibrate faster"), but they oscillate still around the recognizable geometry of the molecule.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] To get a feeling for the probability that the vibration of molecule may be thermally excited, we inspect the Boltzmann factor *β* ≡ exp(−⁠Δ*E*/*kT*⁠), where Δ*E* is the excitation energy of the vibrational mode, *k* the Boltzmann constant and *T* the absolute temperature.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] (The reciprocal centimeter is an energy unit that is commonly used in infrared spectroscopy; 1 cm−1 corresponds to 1.23984×10−4 eV).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] When an excitation energy is 500 cm−1, then about 8.9 percent of the molecules are thermally excited at room temperature.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] To put this in perspective: the lowest excitation vibrational energy in water is the bending mode (about 1600 cm−1).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] Thus, at room temperature less than 0.07 percent of all the molecules of a given amount of water will vibrate faster than at absolute zero.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] As stated above, rotation hardly influences the molecular geometry.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] But, as a quantum mechanical motion, it is thermally excited at relatively (as compared to vibration) low temperatures.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] From a classical point of view it can be stated that at higher temperatures more molecules will rotate faster, which implies that they have higher angular velocity and angular momentum.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] In quantum mechanical language: more eigenstates of higher angular momentum become thermally populated with rising temperatures.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] Typical rotational excitation energies are on the order of a few cm−1.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] The results of many spectroscopic experiments are broadened because they involve an averaging over rotational states.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] It is often difficult to extract geometries from spectra at high temperatures, because the number of rotational states probed in the experimental averaging increases with increasing temperature.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] Thus, many spectroscopic observations can only be expected to yield reliable molecular geometries at temperatures close to absolute zero, because at higher temperatures too many higher rotational states are thermally populated.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] Molecules, by definition, are most often held together with covalent bonds involving single, double, and/or triple bonds, where a "bond" is a shared pair of electrons (the other method of bonding between atoms is called ionic bonding and involves a positive cation and a negative anion).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] Molecular geometries can be specified in terms of 'bond lengths', 'bond angles' and 'torsional angles'.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] The bond length is defined to be the average distance between the nuclei of two atoms bonded together in any given molecule.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] A bond angle is the angle formed between three atoms across at least two bonds.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] For four atoms bonded together in a chain, the torsional angle is the angle between the plane formed by the first three atoms and the plane formed by the last three atoms.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] There exists a mathematical relationship among the bond angles for one central atom and four peripheral atoms (labeled 1 through 4) expressed by the following determinant.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] This constraint removes one degree of freedom from the choices of (originally) six free bond angles to leave only five choices of bond angles.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] Molecular geometry is determined by the quantum mechanical behavior of the electrons.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] Using the valence bond approximation this can be understood by the type of bonds between the atoms that make up the molecule.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] When atoms interact to form a chemical bond, the atomic orbitals of each atom are said to combine in a process called orbital hybridisation.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] The two most common types of bonds are sigma bonds (usually formed by hybrid orbitals) and pi bonds (formed by unhybridized p orbitals for atoms of main group elements).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] The geometry can also be understood by molecular orbital theory where the electrons are delocalised.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] An understanding of the wavelike behavior of electrons in atoms and molecules is the subject of quantum chemistry.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] A bond angle is the geometric angle between two adjacent bonds.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] The bond angles in the table below are ideal angles from the simple VSEPR theory, followed by the actual angle for the example given in the following column where this differs.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] For many cases, such as trigonal pyramidal and bent, the actual angle for the example differs from the ideal angle, and examples differ by different amounts.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] For example, the angle in H2S (92°) differs from the tetrahedral angle by much more than the angle for H2O (104.48°) does.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] The greater the number of lone pairs contained in a molecule, the smaller the angles between the atoms of that molecule.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-angle] The VSEPR theory predicts that lone pairs repel each other, thus pushing the different atoms away from them.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] In molecular geometry, **bond length** or **bond distance** is defined as the average distance between nuclei of two bonded atoms in a molecule.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] It is a transferable property of a bond between atoms of fixed types, relatively independent of the rest of the molecule.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] Bond lengths are measured in the solid phase by means of X-ray diffraction, or approximated in the gas phase by microwave spectroscopy.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] A bond between a given pair of atoms may vary between different molecules.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] For example, the carbon to hydrogen bonds in methane are different from those in methyl chloride.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] It is however possible to make generalizations when the general structure is the same.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] A table with experimental single bonds for carbon to other elements is given below.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] By approximation the bond distance between two different atoms is the sum of the individual covalent radii (these are given in the chemical element articles for each element).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] As a general trend, bond distances *decrease* across the *row* in the periodic table and *increase* down a *group*.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] This trend is identical to that of the atomic radius.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] The bond length between two atoms in a molecule depends not only on the atoms but also on such factors as the orbital hybridization and the electronic and steric nature of the substituents.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] The carbon–carbon (C–C) bond length in diamond is 154 pm.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] It is generally considered the average length for a carbon–carbon single bond, but is also the largest bond length that exists for ordinary carbon covalent bonds.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] Since one atomic unit of length (i.e., a Bohr radius) is 52.9177 pm, the C–C bond length is 2.91 atomic units, or approximately three Bohr radii long.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] Current record holder for the longest C-C bond with a length of 180.6 pm is 1,8-Bis(5-hydroxydibenzo[a,d]cycloheptatrien-5-yl)naphthalene, one of many molecules within a category of hexaaryl ethanes, which are derivatives based on hexaphenylethane skeleton.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] Bond is located between carbons C1 and C2 as depicted in a picture below.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] Another notable compound with an extraordinary C-C bond length is tricyclobutabenzene, in which a bond length of 160 pm is reported.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] Longest C-C bond within the cyclobutabenzene category is 174 pm based on X-ray crystallography.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] In this type of compound the cyclobutane ring would force 90° angles on the carbon atoms connected to the benzene ring where they ordinarily have angles of 120°.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] The existence of a very long C–C bond length of up to 290 pm is claimed in a dimer of two tetracyanoethylene dianions, although this concerns a 2-electron-4-center bond.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] This type of bonding has also been observed in neutral phenalenyl dimers.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] The bond lengths of these so-called "pancake bonds" are up to 305 pm.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] Shorter than average C–C bond distances are also possible: alkenes and alkynes have bond lengths of respectively 133 and 120 pm due to increased s-character of the sigma bond.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] In benzene all bonds have the same length: 139 pm.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] Carbon–carbon single bonds increased s-character is also notable in the central bond of diacetylene (137 pm) and that of a certain tetrahedrane dimer (144 pm).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] In propionitrile the cyano group withdraws electrons, also resulting in a reduced bond length (144 pm).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] Squeezing a C–C bond is also possible by application of strain.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] An unusual organic compound exists called In-methylcyclophane with a very short bond distance of 147 pm for the methyl group being squeezed between a triptycene and a phenyl group.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] In an in silico experiment a bond distance of 136 pm was estimated for neopentane locked up in fullerene.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] The smallest theoretical C–C single bond obtained in this study is 131 pm for a hypothetical tetrahedrane derivative.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] The same study also estimated that stretching or squeezing the C–C bond in an ethane molecule by 5 pm required 2.8 or 3.5 kJ/mol, respectively.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-length] Stretching or squeezing the same bond by 15 pm required an estimated 21.9 or 37.7 kJ/mol.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] In chemistry, **bond energy** (*BE*) is one measure of the strength of a chemical bond.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] It is sometimes called the **mean bond**, **bond enthalpy**, **average bond enthalpy**, or **bond strength**.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] IUPAC defines bond energy as the average value of the gas-phase bond-dissociation energy (usually at a temperature of 298.15 K) for all bonds of the same type within the same chemical species.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] The bond dissociation energy (enthalpy) is also referred to as bond disruption energy, bond energy, bond strength, or binding energy (abbreviation: *BDE*, *BE*, or *D*).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] It is defined as the standard enthalpy change of the following fission: R—*X* → R + *X*.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] This equation tells us that the *BDE* for a given bond is equal to the energy of the individual components that make up the bond when they are free and unbonded minus the energy of the components when they are bonded together.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] These energies are given by the enthalpy of formation Δ*Hf*º of the components in each state.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] The enthalpy of formation of a large number of atoms, free radicals, ions, clusters and compounds is available from the websites of NIST, NASA, CODATA, and IUPAC.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] Most authors use the *BDE* values at 298.15 K.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] For example, the carbon–hydrogen bond energy in methane *BE*(C–H) is the enthalpy change (∆*H*) of breaking one molecule of methane into a carbon atom and four hydrogen radicals, divided by four.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] The exact value for a certain pair of bonded elements varies somewhat depending on the specific molecule, so tabulated bond energies are generally averages from a number of selected typical chemical species containing that type of bond.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] Bond energy (*BE*) is the average of all bond-dissociation energies of a single type of bond in a given molecule.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] The bond-dissociation energies of several different bonds of the same type can vary even within a single molecule.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] For example, a water molecule is composed of two O–H bonds bonded as H–O–H.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] Although the two bonds are the equivalent in the original symmetric molecule, the bond-dissociation energy of an oxygen–hydrogen bond varies slightly depending on whether or not there is another hydrogen atom bonded to the oxygen atom.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] Thus, the bond energy of a molecule of water is 461.5 kJ/mol (110.3 kcal/mol).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] When the bond is broken, the bonding electron pair will split equally to the products.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] This process is called homolytic bond cleavage (homolytic cleavage; homolysis) and results in the formation of radicals.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] The strength of a bond can be estimated by comparing the atomic radii of the atoms that form the bond to the length of bond itself.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] For example, the atomic radius of boron is estimated at 85 pm, while the length of the B–B bond in Diboron tetrachloride, B2Cl4 is 175 pm.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] This ratio is slightly larger than 1, indicating that the bond itself is slightly longer than the expected minimum overlap between the two boron atoms' valence electron clouds.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] Thus, we can conclude that this bond is a rather weak single bond.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] In another example, the atomic radius of rhenium is 135 pm, with a Re–Re bond length of 224 pm in the compound [Re2Cl8]−2.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] This ratio is notably lower than 1, indicating that there is a large amount of overlap between the valence electron clouds of the two rhenium atoms.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] From this data, we can conclude that this is a very strong bond.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] Experimentally, the Re-Re bond in [Re2Cl8]−2 was found to be a quadruple bond.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] This method of determination is most useful for covalently bonded compounds.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] In ionic compounds, the electronegativity of the two atoms bonding together has a major effect on their bond energy.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] The extent of this effect is described by the compound's lattice energy, where a more negative lattice energy corresponds to a stronger force of attraction between the ions.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] Generally, greater differences in electronegativity correspond to stronger ionic bonds.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] For example, the compound sodium chloride (NaCl) has a lattice energy of −786 kJ/mol with an electronegativity difference of 2.23 between sodium and chlorine.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/bond-strength] Meanwhile, the compound sodium iodide (NaI) has a lower lattice energy of −704 kJ/mol with a similarly lower electronegativity difference of 1.73 between sodium and iodine.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] The major isotope of carbon, the 12C isotope, has a spin quantum number of zero, so is not magnetically active and therefore not detectable by NMR.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] 13C, with a spin quantum number of 1/2, is less abundant (1.1%), whereas other popular nuclei are 100% abundant, e.g.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] 13C NMR spectroscopy is much less sensitive (ca. by 4 orders of magnitude) to carbon than 1H NMR spectroscopy is to hydrogen, because of the lower abundance (1.1%) of 13C compared to 1H (>99%), and because of a lower (0.702 vs.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] Stated equivalently, the gyromagnetic ratio (6.728284 107 rad T−1 s−1) is only 1/4th that of 1H.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] On the other hand, the sensitivity of 13C NMR spectroscopy benefits to some extent from nuclear Overhauser effect, which enhances signal intensity for non-quaternary 13C atoms.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] The disadvantages in "receptivity" are compensated by the high sensitivity of 13C NMR signals to the chemical environment of the nucleus, i.e. the chemical shift "dispersion" is great, covering nearly 250 ppm.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] This dispersion reflects the fact that non-1H nuclei are strongly influenced by excited states ("paramagnetic" contribution to shielding tensor.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] This paramagnetic contribution is unrelated to paramagnetism).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] For example, most 1H NMR signals for most organic compounds are within 15 ppm.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] The chemical shift reference standard for 13C is the carbons in tetramethylsilane (TMS), whose chemical shift is set as 0.0 ppm at every temperature.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] Homonuclear 13C-13C coupling is normally only observed in samples that are enriched with 13C.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] The *trends* in J(1H,13C) and J(13C,13C) are similar, except that J(1H,13C are smaller owing to the modest value of the 13C nuclear magnetic moment.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] Values for 2J(1H,13C) are near 5 Hz and often are negative.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] As a consequence of low receptivity, 13C NMR spectroscopy suffers from complications not encountered in proton NMR spectroscopy.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] Many measures can be implemented to compensate for the low receptivity of this nucleus.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] For example, high field magnets with wider internal bores are capable of accepting larger sample tubes (typically 10 mm in diameter for 13C NMR versus 5 mm for 1H NMR).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] Relaxation reagents allow more rapid pulsing.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] A typical relaxation agent is chromium(III) acetylacetonate.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] For a typical sample, recording a 13C NMR spectrum may require several hours, compared to 15–30 minutes for 1H NMR.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] The nuclear dipole is weaker, the difference in energy between alpha and beta states is one-quarter that of proton NMR, and the Boltzmann population difference is correspondingly less.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] One final measure to compensate for low receptivity is isotopic enrichment.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] Some NMR probes, called cryoprobes, offer 20x signal enhancement relative to ordinary NMR probes.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] In cryoprobes, the RF generating and receiving electronics are maintained at ~ 25K using helium gas, which greatly enhances their sensitivity.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] The trade-off is that cryoprobes are costly.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] Another potential complication results from the presence of large one bond J-coupling constants between carbon and hydrogen (typically from 100 to 250 Hz).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] While potentially informative, these couplings can complicate the spectra and reduce sensitivity.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] For these reasons, 13C-NMR spectra are usually recorded with proton NMR decoupling.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] Couplings between carbons can be ignored due to the low natural abundance of 13C.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] Hence in contrast to typical proton NMR spectra, which show multiplets for each proton position, carbon NMR spectra show a single peak for each chemically non-equivalent carbon atom.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] In further contrast to 1H NMR, the intensities of the signals are often not proportional to the number of equivalent 13C atoms.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] Instead, signal intensity is strongly influenced by (and proportional to) the number of surrounding spins (typically 1H).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] Integrations are more quantitative if the delay times are long, i.e. if the delay times greatly exceed relaxation times.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] The most common modes of recording 13C spectra are proton-noise decoupling (also known as noise-, proton-, or broadband- decoupling), off-resonance decoupling, and gated decoupling.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] These modes are meant to address the large J values for 13C - H (110–320 Hz), 13C - C - H (5–60 Hz), and 13C - C - C - H (5–25 Hz) which otherwise make completely proton coupled 13C spectra difficult to interpret.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] With proton-noise decoupling, in which most spectra are run, a noise decoupler strongly irradiates the sample with a broad (approximately 1000 Hz) range of radio frequencies covering the range (such as 100 MHz for a 23,486 gauss field) at which protons change their nuclear spin.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] The rapid changes in proton spin create an effective heteronuclear decoupling, increasing carbon signal strength on account of the nuclear Overhauser effect (NOE) and simplifying the spectrum so that each non-equivalent carbon produces a singlet peak.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] Both the atoms, carbon and hydrogen exhibit spins and are NMR active.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] The nuclear Overhauser Effect is in general, showing up when one of two different types of atoms is irradiated while the NMR spectrum of the other type is determined.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] If the absorption intensities of the observed (i.e., non-irradiated) atom change, enhancement occurs.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] The effect can be either positive or negative, depending on which atom types are involved.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] The relative intensities are unreliable because some carbons have a larger spin-lattice relaxation time and others have weaker NOE enhancement.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] In gated decoupling, the noise decoupler is gated on early in the free induction delay but gated off for the pulse delay.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] This largely prevents NOE enhancement, allowing the strength of individual 13C peaks to be meaningfully compared by integration, at a cost of half to two-thirds of the overall sensitivity.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] With off-resonance decoupling, the noise decoupler irradiates the sample at 1000–2000 Hz upfield or 2000–3000 Hz downfield of the proton resonance frequency.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] This retains couplings between protons immediately adjacent to 13C atoms but most often removes the others, allowing narrow multiplets to be visualized with one extra peak per bound proton (unless bound methylene protons are non-equivalent, in which case a pair of doublets may be observed).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] Signals from quaternary carbons and other carbons with no attached protons are always absent (due to the lack of attached protons).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] The polarization transfer from 1H to 13C has the secondary advantage of increasing the sensitivity over the normal 13C spectrum (which has a modest enhancement from the nuclear Overhauser effect (NOE) due to the 1H decoupling).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] Another useful way of determining how many protons a carbon in a molecule is bonded to is to use an **attached proton test** (APT), which distinguishes between carbon atoms with even or odd number of attached hydrogens.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] Even though this technique does not distinguish fully between CHn groups, it is so easy and reliable that it is frequently employed as a first attempt to assign peaks in the spectrum and elucidate the structure.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] Additionally, signals from quaternary carbons and other carbons with no attached protons are still detectable, so in many cases an additional conventional 13C spectrum is not required, which is an advantage over DEPT.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] It is, however, sometimes possible that a CH and CH2 signal have coincidentally equivalent chemical shifts resulting in annulment in the APT spectrum due to the opposite phases.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/carbon-13-nmr] For this reason the conventional 13C{1H} spectrum or HSQC are occasionally also acquired.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/centimetre] A **centimetre** (International spelling) or **centimeter** (American English), with SI symbol **cm**, is a unit of length in the International System of Units (SI) equal to one hundredth of a metre, *centi-* being the SI prefix for a factor of ⁠1/100⁠.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/centimetre] Equivalently, there are 100 centimetres in 1 metre.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/centimetre] The centimetre is the base unit of length in the now deprecated centimetre–gram–second (CGS) system of units.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/centimetre] Though for many physical quantities, SI prefixes for factors of 103—like *milli-* and *kilo-*—are often preferred by technicians, the centimetre remains a practical unit of length for many everyday measurements; for instance, human height is commonly measured in centimetres.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/centimetre] A centimetre is approximately the width of the fingernail of an average adult person.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/centimetre] One millilitre is defined as one cubic centimetre, under the SI system of units.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/centimetre] These characters are each equal in size to one Chinese character and are typically used only with East Asian, fixed-width CJK fonts.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] In thermodynamics, a **critical point** (or **critical state**) is the end point of a phase equilibrium curve.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] One example is the liquid–vapor critical point, the end point of the pressure–temperature curve that designates conditions under which a liquid and its vapor can coexist.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] At higher temperatures, the gas comes into a supercritical phase, and so cannot be liquefied by pressure alone.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] At the critical point, defined by a *critical temperature* *T*c and a *critical pressure* *p*c, phase boundaries vanish.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] Other examples include the liquid–liquid critical points in mixtures, and the ferromagnet–paramagnet transition (Curie temperature) in the absence of an external magnetic field.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] The liquid–vapor critical point was the first critical point to be discovered, and it remains the best known and most studied one.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] The figure shows the schematic *P-T* diagram of a *pure substance* (as opposed to mixtures, which have additional state variables and richer phase diagrams, discussed below).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] The commonly known phases *solid*, *liquid* and *vapor* are separated by phase boundaries, i.e. pressure–temperature combinations where two phases can coexist.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] At the triple point, all three phases can coexist.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] However, the liquid–vapor boundary terminates in an endpoint at some *critical temperature* *T*c and *critical pressure* *p*c.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] In the *vicinity* of the critical point, the physical properties of the liquid and the vapor change dramatically, with both phases becoming even more similar.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] For instance, liquid water under normal conditions is nearly incompressible, has a low thermal expansion coefficient, has a high dielectric constant, and is an excellent solvent for electrolytes.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] Near the critical point, all these properties change into the exact opposite: water becomes compressible, expandable, a poor dielectric, a bad solvent for electrolytes, and mixes more readily with nonpolar gases and organic molecules.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] The existence of a critical point was first discovered by Charles Cagniard de la Tour in 1822 and named by Dmitri Mendeleev in 1860 and Thomas Andrews in 1869.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] Cagniard showed that CO2 could be liquefied at 31 °C at a pressure of 73 atm, but not at a slightly higher temperature, even under pressures as high as 3000 atm.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] However, the van der Waals equation, based on a mean-field theory, does not hold near the critical point.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] In particular, it predicts wrong scaling laws.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] The principle of corresponding states indicates that substances at equal reduced pressures and temperatures have equal reduced volumes.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] This relationship is approximately true for many substances, but becomes increasingly inaccurate for large values of *p*r.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] For some gases, there is an additional correction factor, called *Newton's correction*, added to the critical temperature and critical pressure calculated in this manner.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] These are empirically derived values and vary with the pressure range of interest.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] The liquid–liquid critical point of a solution, which occurs at the *critical solution temperature*, occurs at the limit of the two-phase region of the phase diagram.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] In other words, it is the point at which an infinitesimal change in some thermodynamic variable (such as temperature or pressure) leads to separation of the mixture into two distinct liquid phases, as shown in the polymer–solvent phase diagram to the right.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] Two types of liquid–liquid critical points are the upper critical solution temperature (UCST), which is the hottest point at which cooling induces phase separation, and the lower critical solution temperature (LCST), which is the coldest point at which heating induces phase separation.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/critical-point-chemistry] From a theoretical standpoint, the liquid–liquid critical point represents the temperature–concentration extremum of the spinodal curve (as can be seen in the figure to the right).
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/lithium-tantalate-data-page] This page provides supplementary chemical data on lithium tantalate.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/lithium-tantalate-data-page] The handling of this chemical may incur notable safety precautions.
[src:lithium-tantalate-data-page/lithium-tantalate-data-page] It is highly recommend that you seek the Material Safety Datasheet (MSDS) for this chemical from a reliable source such as SIRI, and follow its directions.
